  section.page-section
    .container.px-4.px-lg-5
      .row.justify-content-center
        .col-lg-8

          p.lead.mt-5
            | "Rehab is too expensive." It is the most common reason people in active addiction hesitate to ask for help. While private, luxury rehabs can cost tens of thousands of dollars, Washington State's Medicaid program—known as **Apple Health**—covers comprehensive substance use disorder treatment for low-income residents. If you have no income, you are likely eligible right now.

          hr.my-5

          h2.mt-4
            i.bi.bi-check2-circle.text-primary.me-2
            | What Does Apple Health Cover in Spokane?
          p
            | Unlike some states, Washington treats addiction as a fundamental medical condition. If a licensed clinician assesses you and determines that treatment is medically necessary, Apple Health covers a vast array of services:
          ul
            li
              strong Medical Detoxification:
              |  Supervised inpatient withdrawal management to keep you safe when detoxing from alcohol, benzos, or severe opioid use.
            li
              strong Intensive Outpatient Programs (IOP):
              |  Group and individual therapy sessions at a local clinic multiple times a week.
            li
              strong Residential Inpatient Rehab:
              |  Living at a treatment facility for 30, 60, or 90 days.
            li
              strong Medication-Assisted Treatment (MAT):
              |  Full coverage for prescriptions like Suboxone, Vivitrol, or Methadone to treat opioid or alcohol addiction.

          h2.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-person-plus.text-primary.me-2
            | Am I Eligible for Apple Health (Medicaid)?
          p
            | In Washington, Medicaid eligibility for adults (aged 19–64) is simply based on income levels. As of 2025-2026, a single adult making less than approximately $1,732 a month (before taxes) qualifies. If you have children or dependents, that income limit is significantly higher.
          p
            | **Crucially:** If you are currently unemployed because of your addiction, you qualify immediately.

          h2.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-laptop.text-primary.me-2
            | How to Apply Today
          p
            | You can apply for Apple Health entirely online. The process usually takes less than 30 minutes.
          ul
            li
              strong Online at Washington Healthplanfinder:
              |  Go to <a href="https://www.wahealthplanfinder.org/" target="_blank">wahealthplanfinder.org</a> and fill out an application. If you meet the income requirements, your coverage often begins on the first day of the month you applied.
            li
              strong By Phone:
              |  Call the Healthplanfinder Customer Support Center at 1-855-923-4633.
            li
              strong In-Person Help in Spokane:
              |  If you are overwhelmed or don't have internet access, local organizations like **CHAS Health** employ "Navigators" whose entire job is to sit down with you and help you fill out the application for free. Just walk into a local clinic and ask for a Navigator.

          h2.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-building.text-primary.me-2
            | Finding Rehab Centers That Accept Medicaid
          p
            | Once you are approved, you need to find a "state-certified behavioral health agency" in Spokane that accepts Medicaid (specifically, your Managed Care Organization like Molina, Coordinated Care, or Community Health Plan of WA).
           
          p
            | Almost all major community behavioral health centers in Spokane accept Apple Health, including:
          ul
            li Frontier Behavioral Health
            li Excelsior Wellness
            li Spokane Regional Health District (Treatment Services)
            li American Behavioral Health Systems (ABHS)

          hr.my-5

          .card.border-0.shadow.text-center.p-5.mb-4(style="border-radius: 16px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0d6efd11 0%, #0d6efd22 100%);")
            i.bi.bi-hospital.display-4.text-primary.mb-3
